at point 2).\n\nExample 2:\n\n\nInput: obstacles = [0,1,1,3,3,0]\nOutput: 0\nExplanation: There are no obstacles on lane 2. No side jumps are required.\n\nExample 3:\n\n\nInput: obstacles = [0,2,1,0,3,0]\nOutput: 2\nExplanation: The optimal solution is shown by the arrows above. There are 2 side jumps.\n\n \nConstraints:\n\nobstacles.length == n + 1\n1 <= n <= 5 * 105\n0 <= obstacles[i] <= 3\nobstacles[0] == obstacles[n] == 0\n\n\n\n### Format: You will use the following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def minSideJumps(self, obstacles: List[int]) -> int:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nfrom typing import List\nimport math\n\nclass Solution:\n    def minSideJumps(self, obstacles: List[int]) -> int:\n        # Initialize the minimum side jumps required to reach each lane at the starting point\n        # Starting at lane 2, so initially, side jumps to reach lane 1 and lane 3 are 1 each\n        dp = [1, 0, 1]  # dp[0] is lane 1, dp[1] is lane 2, dp[2] is lane 3\n        \n        for i in range(1, len(obstacles)):\n            # If there's an obstacle in a lane, set the side jumps to infinity for that lane\n            new_dp = [math.inf if obstacles[i] == j + 1 else dp[j] for j in range(3)]\n            \n            # Update the side jumps for each lane considering possible side jumps\n            for j in range(3):\n                if obstacles[i] != j + 1:\n                    for k in range(3):\n                        if j != k and obstacles[i] != k + 1:\n                            new_dp[j] = min(new_dp[j], new_dp[k] + 1)\n            \n            dp = new_dp\n        \n        # Return the minimum side jumps required to reach any lane at the end point\n        return min(dp)\n```\n\nThis solution uses dynamic programming to keep track of the minimum side jumps required to reach each lane at each point. It iterates through each point and updates the side jumps needed based on the presence of obstacles and possible side jumps. The final result is the minimum side jumps required to reach any lane at the end point.", "estimated_date": 1618099200000}